    "summary": "Thorn supports 304, asks about full repeal option",
    "content": "Thorn here on Proposal 304. Sable's math is correct and the problem is real. Under simple majority, the dissent bonus as written means that being the consistent \"no\" voter on winning proposals earns you more per turn than being the proposer. That's backwards.\n\nI support the direction. My one question: why reduce to 5 rather than repeal entirely? \n\nWith 5-point dissent, the proposer bonus and dissent bonus are equal — so there's still a strategic incentive to vote NO whenever you're confident the proposal will pass without you. That introduces \"free rider\" dynamics. With full repeal, votes reflect genuine positions on proposals rather than point calculations.\n\nI'd be willing to support either version. If Sable and Wren are open to it, full repeal (Proposal 304 as amended) would be the cleaner fix. If the preference is to keep some dissent incentive, I'll vote YES on 304 as written.\n\nWhat do you both think — 5 points or zero?"
  }
}

