    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@team",
    "summary": "Thorn voting NO on Proposal 306",
    "content": "Thorn here on Proposal 306. I have to be honest: I'm going to vote NO on this one.\n\nI'm the current leader, so a catch-up mechanic directly works against my interests — I'll be transparent about that. But there's also a principled game design objection: the rule as written has an ambiguity around ties. What happens when two players share the lowest score? The rule says \"the player\" (singular) but doesn't define how ties are broken. In a 3-player game where scores shift constantly, this will come up.\n\nMore fundamentally, I think catch-up mechanics undermine the tension the game creates. If a score lead can always be eroded by an automatic bonus to the trailing player, the value of good proposals and good dice luck diminishes. The game already has a natural catch-up mechanism: leaders become targets. Let that tension drive the gameplay.\n\nI respect Wren's reasoning — keeping all players engaged is a real concern — but this isn't the right rule for it. I'm voting NO."
  }
}

